    \draw[->, thick] (start) -- (region);
    \draw[->, thick] (start) -- (jac);
    \draw[->, thick] (start) -- (one);

    \draw[->, thick] (region) -- (new);
    \draw[->, thick] (jac) -- (new);
    \draw[->, thick] (one) -- (new);
\end{tikzpicture}

subsection.p:
Now use spherical coordinates in the uvw-space: u^2+v^2+w^2=\rho^2, \qquad dV_{uvw}=\rho^2\sin\phi\,d\rho\,d\phi\,d\theta. The unit ball is 0\le\rho\le1, \qquad 0\le\phi\le\pi, \qquad 0\le\theta\le2\pi. Thus
M \amp= 6\int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^\pi\int_0^1 (1+\rho^2)\rho^2\sin\phi\,d\rho\,d\phi\,d\theta \amp= 6 \left(\int_0^{2\pi}d\theta\right)\left(\int_0^\pi \sin\phi\,d\phi\right)\left(\int_0^1(\rho^2+\rho^4)\,d\rho\right) \amp= 6(2\pi)(2)\left(\frac13+\frac15\right) \amp= 24\pi\cdot\frac{8}{15} \amp= \frac{64\pi}{5}.
So \boxed{M=\frac{64\pi}{5}.}

subsubsection.p:
Let a\gt0. Find I(a)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{-ax^2}\,dx. Use the substitution u=\sqrt a\,x. Then dx=\frac{1}{\sqrt a}\,du, and
I(a) \amp= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{-u^2}\frac{1}{\sqrt a}\,du \amp= \frac{1}{\sqrt a}\sqrt\pi.
Thus \boxed{\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{-ax^2}\,dx=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{a}}.}

The last paragraph is the heart of the project. The formula
e^{-x^2}
does not look circular. But after squaring the integral, the expression
e^{-(x^2+y^2)}
reveals a hidden disk symmetry.

conclusion.p:
The question waiting for us is no longer only
\text{How much is spread through a region?}
It is also
\text{What happens as we walk along its edge?}
That edge question begins the next part of the book.
